TEXT(&beginproblem);
$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;
$a=random(1,10,1)*random(-1,1,2);
$b=random(1,10,1)*random(-1,1,2);
$c=random(1,10,1)*random(-1,1,2);

BEGIN_TEXT

$PAR$HR$PAR
(a) You are given the point \((1,\pi/2)\) in polar coordinates.

$PAR
(i) Find another pair of polar coordinates for this point such that \(r > 0\) and \(2\pi \le \theta < 4\pi.\)

$PAR
\(r = \)  \{ans_rule(15)\}

$PAR
\(\theta = \)  \{ans_rule(15)\}

$PAR
(ii) Find another pair of polar coordinates for this point such that \(r < 0\) and \(0 \le \theta < 2\pi.\)

$PAR
\(r = \)  \{ans_rule(15)\}

$PAR
\(\theta = \)  \{ans_rule(15)\}

$PAR$HR$PAR
(b) You are given the point \((-2,\pi/4)\) in polar coordinates.

$PAR
(i) Find another pair of polar coordinates for this point such that \(r > 0\) and \(2\pi \le \theta < 4\pi.\)

$PAR
\(r = \)  \{ans_rule(15)\}

$PAR
\(\theta = \)  \{ans_rule(15)\}

$PAR
(ii) Find another pair of polar coordinates for this point such that \(r < 0\) and \(-2\pi \le \theta < 0.\)

$PAR
\(r = \)  \{ans_rule(15)\}

$PAR
\(\theta = \)  \{ans_rule(15)\}

$PAR$HR$PAR
(c) You are given the point \((3,2)\) in polar coordinates.

$PAR
(i) Find another pair of polar coordinates for this point such that \(r > 0\) and \(2\pi \le \theta < 4\pi.\)

$PAR
\(r = \)  \{ans_rule(15)\}

$PAR
\(\theta = \)  \{ans_rule(15)\}

$PAR
(ii) Find another pair of polar coordinates for this point such that \(r < 0\) and \(0 \le \theta < 2\pi.\)

$PAR
\(r = \)  \{ans_rule(15)\}

$PAR
\(\theta = \)  \{ans_rule(15)\}

$PAR$HR

END_TEXT

ANS(num_cmp("1"));
ANS(num_cmp("5*pi/2"));
ANS(num_cmp("-1"));
ANS(num_cmp("3*pi/2"));

ANS(num_cmp("2"));
ANS(num_cmp("13*pi/4"));
ANS(num_cmp("-2"));
ANS(num_cmp("-7*pi/4"));

ANS(num_cmp("3"));
ANS(num_cmp("2+2*pi"));
ANS(num_cmp("-3"));
ANS(num_cmp("2+pi"));

